{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e681c2e0-53c9-4b84-9196-896b7474bc88","content":"Use **dotnet-trace** — it's the simplest option for .NET apps and doesn't require Visual Studio or PerfView setup.\n\n### Quick steps\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or convert for other tools:\n\n```powershell\n# Convert to SpeedScope format (opens in https://speedscope.app)\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing\n\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper analysis, OS-level ETW events, GC details |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick live check (`cpu-usage`, `threadpool-queue-length`) before tracing |\n\n### Tip — triage first with counters\n\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\n\nThis tells you instantly if the CPU burn is from GC (`% Time in GC`), thread pool starvation, or your own code — so you know what to look for in the trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"76e9a89f-4dd6-48f8-8af7-dde2cd7d67a9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":435,"requestId":"A0C8:1BD058:C6E2B8:F490FB:6A013105"},"id":"07413f13-e985-4507-964f-182508d3bd92","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:29:54.697Z","parentId":"c6f800c8-43d8-47e9-b6f8-15295a4b8e86"}
